07142nam a22010455i 9789048537211DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20202020ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485372117 a10.1515/97890485372112doi  a(DE-B1597)546161  a(OCoLC)1151851557  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 7aHIS0370902bisacsh00aEarly Modern Écologies :bBeyond English Ecocriticism /ced. by Usher, Pauline Goul. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (310 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEnvironmental Humanities in Pre-Modern Cultures00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Off the Human Track : Montaigne, Deleuze, and the Materialization of Philosophy -- tPart 1. Dark(Ish) Ecologies -- t2. Du Bartas Responding to Morton’s Milton : A Bodily Route to the Ecological Thought -- t3. ‘When is a meadow not a meadow?’ : Dark Ecology and Fields of Conflict in French Renaissance Poetry -- t4. Equipment for Living with Hyperobjects : Proverbs in Ronsard’s Franciade -- t5. Is Ecology Absurd? Diogenes and the End of Civilization -- tPart 2. Nature’s Cultures -- t6. Between Nature and Culture : The Integrated Ecology of Renaissance Climate Theories -- t7. Almost Encountering Ronsard’s Rose -- t8. Renascent Nature in the Ruins: Joachim du Bellay’s Antiquitez de Rome -- tPart 3. Groundings -- t9. An Inconvenient Bodin: Latour and the Treasure Seekers -- t10. Reading Olivier de Serres circa 1600: Between Economy and Ecology -- t11. Montaigne’s Plants in Movement -- tEpilogue -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEarly Modern Écologies is the first collective volume to offer perspectives on the relationship between contemporary ecological thought and early modern French literature. If Descartes spoke of humans as being "masters and possessors of Nature" in the seventeenth century, the writers taken up in this volume arguably demonstrated a more complex and urgent understanding of the human relationship to our shared planet. Opening up a rich archive of literary and non-literary texts produced by Montaigne and his contemporaries, this volume foregrounds not how ecocriticism renews our understanding of a literary corpus, but rather how that corpus causes us to re-think or to nuance contemporary eco-theory. The sparsely bilingual title (an acute accent on écologies) denotes the primary task at hand: to pluralize (i.e. de-Anglophone-ize) the Environmental Humanities. Featuring established and emerging scholars from Europe and the United States, Early Modern Écologies opens up new dialogues between eco-theorists such as Timothy Morton, Gilles Deleuze, and Bruno Latour and Montaigne, Ronsard, Du Bartas, and Olivier de Serres.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 4aEarly Modern Studies. 4aEnvironment and Sustainability. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aLiterary Theory, Criticism, and History. 4aPhilosophy. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 16th Century.2bisacsh  aEarly Modern.  aEcocriticism.  aEcology.  aFrance.  aLatour.1 aAddis, Kat, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConley, Tom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoul, Pauline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoul, Pauline, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMackenzie, Louisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMelehy, Hassan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiglietti, Sara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOliver, Jennifer, econtrib